node.text:
“I thought, I’m a trans woman. If I worked from outside the system, it’d be harder to voice out people’s aspirations.”⁣
⁣
In Muslim majority Indonesia, trans people are often not accepted in society as they are seen to contravene social norms. In Maumere, the largest city in Flores and a long way from Jakarta, it’s a different story. ⁣
⁣
Hendrika Mayora Victoria Kelan is a trans woman who overcame impossible odds to become Indonesia’s first trans official. She had left the Catholic clergy after coming to terms with her gender identity and had to make a living as a sex worker. Hendrika finally found acceptance after returning home where her community embraced her identity, and even nominated her as a candidate for public office. ⁣
⁣
Hendrika was elected as Head of the Regional Representative Council and her story has since become a source of inspiration for other trans women in her village.⁣
⁣
#vwn #viceworldnews

node.title: Meet Indonesia’s First Elected Trans Official

Memes are some of the most used and ubiquitous images on the internet. If you’ve used the internet over the last decade, there's no chance you’ve not seen one. ⁣
⁣
Political parties and groups of all persuasions have jumped on the meme culture bandwagon, but none more so than the far-right, who have weaponized irony to cloak their hateful ideologies and spread their memes far and wide into non-political spaces. ⁣
⁣
#vwn #viceworldnews

node.title: How the Far Right Use Memes to Recruit

node.text: “Who Let The Dogs Out” was ubiquitous in the early aughts - emanating from sports stadiums, parties, and radio speakers alike. But fewer people know the story behind the the group who performed it, @bahamenmusic, or the man who wrote it, @anslemdouglas64. The song’s unconventional journey spans from crowded baseball stadiums in Seattle to the sandy beaches of the Caribbean. VICE meets the key players involved in the incredible success of the song that left everyone asking, “Who Let the Dogs Out?”

node.title: The Story of 'Who Let The Dogs Out' by Baha Men

“Even with labels like ‘free-range’ and ‘organic’, we still find a lot of abuse and problems in those farms.”⁣
⁣
An undercover investigator for animal rights groups has spent the last 25 years covertly filming at factory farms across the UK and Europe. He’s seen animals beaten for not doing what the workers want and living half-dead in their own excrement. ⁣
⁣
This is the state of farms everywhere, even places making products labelled “local”, “organic” or "free-range".⁣
⁣
Informer is a series where we hear the anonymised confessions and insights of people in positions of power on the inside of important institutions.⁣
⁣

node.title: The Disgusting Things I Witnessed in Factory Farms

Most scam callers will do whatever it takes to steal your money. Many feel no guilt, but a small few know they are doing the wrong thing. Casey, a former scammer in India who is now undercover in call centers, works with investigators to gather evidence and help warn would-be scam victims.

In a series of candid interviews, Fakes, Frauds & Scammers relives some of the most audacious scams and fraudulent stunts of our time from the mouths of the perpetrators themselves. Whether it’s money, fame or simply an addiction to lying, we find out what motivated these tricksters and whether the highs, lows and ramifications were worth it in the end.

#vwn #viceworldnews

node.title: I Went Undercover in a Scam Call Center

"The advantage is with the bad guy.”

node.text:
Medical tourism to Mexico from the US is huge, with an estimated three million inbound medical travellers in 2020 alone. Medication is cheaper in Mexico than the US, and you can buy most drugs without a prescription. ⁣
⁣
While most people are able to find the care they desperately need, some are also buying cheap unregulated medicine without knowing it’s fake. The ingredients can be completely unknown and in recent years, the DEA have seized counterfeit medication laced with the deadly opioid fentanyl. ⁣
⁣
Watch the full film on YouTube.⁣
⁣
#vwn #viceworldnews

node.title: Cartels Are Making Millions on Fentanyl-Laced Medicine

node.text:
From the 1940s onward China experienced a demographic boom which doubled the country’s population to almost one billion by the late 1970s. Desperate to prevent an excess 400 million births that would have compromised the country’s plans for financial growth, the Chinese government introduced its so-called one-child policy in 1979, limiting how the number of children couples were allowed to have by law. To avoid punishment, some felt forced to giving up their children, while other children listed for international adoption were forcibly taken away from their families. ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
The gallery features photographs by Youqine Lefèvre exploring the far-reaching consequences of China's disastrous birth program through her own adoption. ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Link in bio for the full story. ⁠⁠

“I thought, I’m a trans woman. If I worked from outside the system, it’d be harder to voice out people’s aspirations.”⁣
⁣
In Muslim majority Indonesia, trans people are often not accepted in society as they are seen to contravene social norms. In Maumere, the largest city in Flores and a long way from Jakarta, it’s a different story. ⁣
⁣
Hendrika Mayora Victoria Kelan is a trans woman who overcame impossible odds to become Indonesia’s first trans official. She had left the Catholic clergy after coming to terms with her gender identity and had to make a living as a sex worker. Hendrika finally found acceptance after returning home where her community embraced her identity, and even nominated her as a candidate for public office. ⁣
⁣
Hendrika was elected as Head of the Regional Representative Council and her story has since become a source of inspiration for other trans women in her village.⁣
⁣

node.text:
One volunteer counted 261 dead migratory birds surrounding the World Trade Center complex on Tuesday morning. ⁠
⁠
Each year, it’s estimated that between 90,000 and 230,000 migratory birds are killed in NYC by colliding with building glass, a statistic made even more striking by the fact that the migratory season lasts just six weeks. When these birds collide into skyscrapers, they suffer two concussions: one when they hit the glass, and another when they fall to the ground. ⁠
⁠
Birds don’t understand reflections, nor can they detect clear glass as a physical barrier. Bright lights at night also attract nocturnal migratory birds, potentially by disrupting their internal sense of direction. In short, glass buildings with their lights on at night are death traps for young migratory songbirds.⁠
⁠
If you come across a bird on a city street, you should pick it up: if it moves its legs, it’s not dead, rather unconscious and hypothermic, according to Rita McMahon, director of the Wild Bird Fund. ⁠
⁠
She recommended putting the bird in a brown paper bag for an hour, then if it begins making “tap dancing” sounds, seeing if it flies around when released in a small, dark room. If so, people should take the bird to their nearest wildlife rehabilitation center if able, or release the bird into the wild, she added. But the most important thing you can do is turn off the lights when you leave the office.⁠
⁠
 Link in bio for more.

"How are erections measured while a man sleeps? Two small rings are placed around the penis, one at the tip and one at the base," one message on a U.S. military website read.⁠

Over the past year, various government and military websites have been hosting some walls of text you wouldn't ordinarily expect to see on .gov sites. node.text:
Take the England football fan who went viral this summer after shoving a flare up his ass and jubilantly snorting keys of white powder on film. “I was off my face and I loved every minute,” he later told the Sun. But the guy was never questioned by police – so what figures? Does that mean anyone can post anything?⁠
⁠
Turns out, your posts can get you in trouble with the law – but not always in the ways you’d think. With that in mind, more on what you need to know about posting illegal shit on social media at the link in bio 🔗

Last year, when the US went through COVID-related lockdowns, 8.6% of US college students and 7.6% of young adults said they had used psychedelics in the last 12 months, compared to 4.1% and 4.3% in 2017. ⁠
⁠
This uptick comes during an era where LSD, psilocybin, ketamine and MDMA are being trialed and prescribed to treat a range of medical issues such as depression and PTSD, while the legal barriers to these drugs being used in therapy are falling away. Full story at link in bio.

node.text:
Begum was speaking from the camp in Syria where she is currently living. The 22-year-old from East London travelled to Syria to join ISIS when she was a 15-year-old school girl, and married convicted terrorist Yago Riedijk, originally from the Netherlands. ⁠
⁠
“I know it’s very hard for the British people to try and forgive me because they have lived in fear of ISIS and lost loved ones because of ISIS, but I also have lived in fear of ISIS and I also lost loved ones because of ISIS, so I can sympathise with them in that way,” she said in a Good Morning Britain interview.
⁠
In 2019 Begum said that the Manchester Arena attack, in which 22 people were killed by a pro-ISIS suicide bomber, was “justified” because of airstrikes that killed people in Syria.⁠
⁠
